The [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University) (SWJTU, or as it's known in the more traditional script, 西南交通大学) stands as a prominent [national](/National_university) [public](/Public_university) institution, specifically classified as a [science and engineering university](/Types_of_universities_and_colleges_in_China). It is currently situated in the vibrant city of [Chengdu](/Chengdu), within the [Sichuan](/Sichuan) province of [China](/China). Its operational framework places it under the direct affiliation of the [Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China](/Ministry_of_Education_of_the_People%27s_Republic_of_China). More than just a university, SWJTU holds the distinguished status of a [national key university](/National_Key_Universities), a designation that implies significant governmental support and strategic importance. This key status is further underscored by its unique co-sponsorship arrangement, involving not only the [Ministry of Education](/Ministry_of_Education_of_the_People%27s_Republic_of_China) but also the powerful [China Railway Corporation](/China_Railway_Corporation), the provincial government of [Sichuan](/Sichuan), and the municipal government of [Chengdu](/Chengdu). Such multifaceted backing reflects its critical role in national development, particularly within the railway sector.

Beyond its foundational structure, the university is deeply integrated into China's higher education strategic plans. It is a recognized participant in both [Project 211](/Project_211), a major initiative launched in the mid-1990s to cultivate approximately 100 top universities and key disciplinary faculties for the 21st century, and the more recent, ambitious [Double First-Class Construction](/Double_First-Class_Construction) plan, which aims to develop world-class universities and disciplines.

Founded in the rather distant past of 1896, SWJTU carries a legacy that positions it as one of China's unequivocally leading engineering universities. Its historical significance is perhaps best encapsulated by its enduring reputation as the "cradle of China's [railway engineers](/Railway_engineering)." This isn't merely a romantic epithet; the institution is genuinely recognized as the birthplace of modern Chinese education across several critical fields: [transportation](/Transportation), [mining](/Mining), [metallurgy](/Metallurgy), and [civil engineering](/Civil_engineering). Over its extensive lifespan, the university has, quite remarkably, navigated through a series of name changes, each reflecting shifts in national policy, location, or strategic focus. These historical appellations include "Imperial Chinese Railway College," "Tangshan Jiaotong University," and "Tangshan Institute of Railway" [1]. One might wonder if they spent more time on rebranding than actual education in those early years, though the results suggest otherwise.

In terms of contemporary standing, SWJTU consistently secures its position among the upper echelons of universities in [China](/China). Its international recognition is noted in various global rankings, for instance, securing a specific placement of 181-190 in The Times Higher Education Asia University Rankings 2016 [2] and achieving a rank of 161 in The Times Higher Education BRICS & Emerging Economies 2016. Such numerical precision in rankings is, apparently, paramount. Furthermore, it was among the initial cohort of institutions to be inducted into the prestigious [Double First Class University Plan](/Double_First_Class_University_Plan) and, prior to that, was a key institution within the former [Project 211](/Project_211). The intellectual capital fostered within its walls is evident in the achievements of its faculty and alumni, who have collectively earned an impressive 57 fellowships to both the United States and China's [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences) [1]. This, by any measure, is a significant contribution to the global scientific and engineering community. To reiterate, and for absolute clarity, it is officially designated a Chinese state [Double First Class University](/Double_First_Class_University_Plan) [3].

## About SWJTU

This section, regrettably, does not [cite](/Wikipedia:Citing_sources) any [sources](/Wikipedia:Verifiability) for its claims. One might assume that an institution of this caliber would demand a more rigorous adherence to [verifiability](/Wikipedia:Verifiability), but here we are. Please help [improve this section](/Special:EditPage/Southwest_Jiaotong_University) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Unsourced material may be challenged and, quite rightly, [removed](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). (October 2024) ([Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal)). Perhaps they're too busy moving campuses to document their own history properly.

Nevertheless, the narrative persists: the university's genesis lies in [Shanhaiguan](/Shanhaiguan_District), [Hebei](/Hebei), in 1896, though its current incarnation firmly resides in [Chengdu](/Chengdu), [Sichuan](/Sichuan). This journey, as you'll note, was not a straight line, but rather a series of strategic (or perhaps forced) relocations. Today, SWJTU sprawls across three distinct campuses, a testament to its growth, or perhaps an inability to settle down. The primary hub is the Xipu campus, a modern and expansive facility that serves as the university's main administrative and academic center. This is complemented by the Jiulidi campus, which is conveniently situated in the bustling downtown area of [Chengdu](/Chengdu), offering a more central urban presence. Further afield, approximately 90 miles to the southwest, lies the Emei campus. This location is rather picturesquely "snuggled" at the foot of [Mount Emei](/Mount_Emei), which, for those unfamiliar, is one of [China](/China)'s four revered [Buddhist](/Buddhism) mountains. A rather serene, almost spiritual, setting for an institution focused on the decidedly material world of engineering, one might muse. These diverse campuses collectively cater to an impressive, if somewhat unwieldy, population of approximately 60,000 students, offering programs across both graduate and undergraduate levels.

The story of its establishment begins, as previously noted, at [Shanhaiguan](/Shanhaiguan_District) in 1896, under the initial guise of the 'Imperial Chinese Railway College.' At that time, it quickly distinguished itself as one of the oldest universities in [China](/China) with a primary focus on engineering. The first significant relocation in its peripatetic history occurred in 1905, when the institution was moved to Tangshan, in [Hebei](/Hebei) Province. During this period, it underwent a series of identity shifts, being successively renamed 'Tangshan Chiao Tung University,' 'Tangshan Railway Institute,' and other variations that reflected its evolving mission and administrative oversight. Another major geographical upheaval saw the university dramatically transplanted to Emei, [Sichuan](/Sichuan) province in 1972. It was at this juncture that it finally adopted its current, and presumably more permanent, name: [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University). Not content with just one relocation to [Sichuan](/Sichuan), 1989 saw the main administrative functions and a significant portion of its academic operations shift once more, this time to [Chengdu](/Chengdu), with the Emei campus transitioning into a dedicated branch campus. The turn of the millennium, specifically 2002, marked the commencement of the Xipu campus's construction in [Chengdu](/Chengdu), a sprawling new development covering an area of over 3,000 [mu](/Mu_(land))—a substantial 200 hectares. This ambitious expansion solidified the university's current, rather complex, operational model: "one university, in two places, with three campuses." A logistical marvel, or perhaps a bureaucratic headache, depending on your perspective.

In its current configuration, the university is a formidable academic enterprise. It comprises an extensive network of 18 schools, complemented by 3 distinct departments, and 2 specialized divisions. Its student body now totals more than 38,000 individuals, supported by a dedicated teaching and administrative staff exceeding 3,900. This substantial workforce includes approximately 1,800 full-time teachers, with a significant contingent of around 1,000 professors and associate professors, providing a deep pool of academic expertise. The institution's academic pedigree is further bolstered by the presence of 3 academicians from the esteemed Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and 2 from the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) among its full-time staff. In addition, there are an impressive 29 academicians from CAS and CAE who lend their invaluable expertise to the university, serving as part-time professors by invitation. The academic offerings are remarkably extensive and diverse, featuring 45 distinct [Doctor of Philosophy](/Doctor_of_Philosophy) (PHD) programs, 95 master's degree accreditation posts, and 61 undergraduate majors—because who doesn't love options? Furthermore, the university hosts 7 post-doctorate research centers, 3 national basic scientific research and teaching talents training bases, 6 national key disciplines, and a coveted [state key laboratory](/State_Key_Laboratories). All very impressive, on paper, and certainly indicative of a robust academic ecosystem.

## History

### Historical Footprints

This section, once again, does not [cite](/Wikipedia:Citing_sources) any [sources](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). It's almost as if historical memory is deemed less important than engineering schematics. Please help [improve this section](/Special:EditPage/Southwest_Jiaotong_University) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Unsourced material may be challenged and, inevitably, [removed](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). (October 2024) ([Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal)). One would think a locomotive driving simulator of a [China Railways HXD3B](/China_Railways_HXD3B) electric locomotive, produced by [CNR Dalian](/CNR_Dalian) and Southwest Jiaotong University, would require more rigorous documentation, but I digress.

The foundational story of [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University) (SWJTU) begins in May 1896, when it was initially established as the Imperial Chinese Railway College at [Shanhaiguan](/Shanhaiguan_District) by the Beiyang Railway Bureau. However, this early iteration was short-lived. In September 1900, due to the destabilizing invasion by the allied forces of the eight imperialist powers—a rather inconvenient geopolitical squabble for an nascent educational institution—it was unfortunately forced to shut down its operations.

After a period of dormancy, the college was re-established in October 1905, this time relocated to Tangshan and renamed the Tangshan Railway Institute. This was under the auspices of the Imperial Railways of North China. Demonstrating an early expansion of its academic scope, in April 1906, it broadened its curriculum to include mining and was accordingly renamed the Tangshan Engineering & Mining College, still under the same railway administration. By January 1908, a shift in governmental oversight occurred, placing the institution, now known simply as the Tangshan Engineering & Mining College, directly under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Posts and Communications. This direct oversight continued until December 1912.

With the establishment of the Republic of [China](/China) in 1912, the Ministry of Posts and Communications was replaced by the Ministry of Transport. Consequently, the college was renamed the Tangshan Railway Institute of the Ministry of Transport, reflecting its new administrative allegiance. Further changes came in August 1913, when, under a joint directive from the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Transport, it was renamed the Tangshan Engineering College. This name endured until July 1921.

The year 1921 marked a significant structural change in [China](/China)'s higher education landscape. The Ministry of Transport of the Beiyang government founded Jiaotong University, establishing its headquarter in Beijing and three distinct branches in Beijing, Tangshan, and Shanghai. The Tangshan institution was thus renamed the Tangshan Institute of Jiaotong University. This structure, however, was also temporary. In September 1922, the Ministry of Transport restructured Jiaotong University, dividing it into two separate entities: Tangshan University and Nanyang University. The school in Tangshan was, for a period, renamed as Tangshan University of the Ministry of Transport.

Further political shifts in February 1928 led to Tangshan University being renamed Tangshan Jiaotong University, following instructions from the Beiyang government. Just four months later, in June 1928, it was rebranded again as the Second Jiaotong University after the National Government's unification of the North and South. In the same year, the Ministry of Transport again restructured Jiaotong University, setting its headquarter in Shanghai. The Tangshan institution was then subsumed under this new structure, becoming the Tangshan Civil Engineering Institute of Jiaotong University.

October 1928 saw the National Government establish the Ministry of Railways, which subsequently took direct jurisdiction over the school. By November of that year, Jiaotong University itself was renamed Jiaotong University of the Ministry of Railways, with its headquarter firmly in Shanghai, and its branches designated as the Peiping Railway Management Institute and the Tangshan Engineering Institute. The Tangshan school was, once more, renamed, becoming the Tangshan Engineering Institute of Jiaotong University. This name persisted through several years of relative stability, from September 1931 to August 1937.

The tranquility was shattered in August 1937 with the outbreak of the Second Sino-Japanese War and the infamous Lu Gou Qiao Incident (Marco Polo Bridge Incident). The campus in Tangshan was occupied by the Japanese army, forcing the university into a series of arduous relocations. Through the determined efforts of its staff and students, the university was re-established in Xiangtan, Hunan, by the end of 1937. In March 1938, the Peiping Railway Management Institute was merged into the Tangshan Engineering Institute, consolidating resources amidst the national crisis. By May, the university was forced to move again, this time to Yang Jiatan, Xiangxiang, Hunan. The war's relentless progression saw Wuhan fall to enemy occupation in 1938, compelling yet another westward relocation for the university. In 1939, classes commendably restarted in Pingyue city (now known as Fuquan City) in Guizhou province.

July 1941 brought a decision from the Ministry of Education to rename the university as the National Tangshan Engineering Institute of Jiaotong University, Peiping Railway Management Institute – a rather unwieldy title that, predictably, aroused controversy within the university community itself. To resolve this, in January 1942, the Ministry of Education established the National Jiaotong University, Guizhou, which formally encompassed both the Tangshan Engineering Institute and the Peiping Railway Management Institute. The war's shadow continued to loom large; in November 1944, due to the Japanese army's occupation of Dushan, Guizhou, the university was once again forced to evacuate, relocating to Bishan, [Sichuan](/Sichuan).

After the arduous Anti-Japanese War concluded, August 1946 saw a decision by the Ministry of Education to rename the institution the National Tangshan Engineering Institute, placing it directly under the Ministry of Education's authority. Critically, it was also moved back to its original site in Tangshan, a welcome return after years of displacement.

The political landscape of [China](/China) underwent a seismic shift in 1949 with the founding of the People's Republic of [China](/China). Consequently, the university was taken over by the Ministry of Railways of the Central Military Commission. A new entity, China Jiaotong University, was established, with its headquarter in Beijing and branches in Tangshan (the former Tangshan Engineering Institute) and Beijing Railway Management Institute. The university in Tangshan was, yet again, renamed, becoming the Tangshan Engineering College of China Jiaotong University.

In August 1950, its name was refined to Tangshan Engineering College of Northern Jiaotong University. A major national restructuring, the "Adjustment of Departments in Chinese Colleges," occurred in 1952. During this period, several key majors including Mining, Metallurgy, Chemicals, Architecture, Water Conservancy, and Communication were moved out of the institution. As a result of this significant departmental realignment, the university was renamed the Tangshan Railway Institute.

The mid-1960s brought another major, centrally mandated relocation. In September 1964, in accordance with a decision by the Ministry of Railways and broader national policies, the university was moved to Emei, [Sichuan](/Sichuan). It was here, in March 1972, that the university finally adopted its present name: [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University). This name, at least, has stuck.

The 1980s saw further strategic adjustments. In 1989, the headquarter of the university was moved to [Chengdu](/Chengdu), with Emei transitioning to a branch campus (which later evolved into one of its distinct campuses). The most recent significant development in its physical footprint occurred in 2002 when the Xipu Campus was founded in [Chengdu](/Chengdu). This expansion solidified the current operational model, which is described as "one university, in two places, with three campuses," a rather complex logistical arrangement for an institution with such a turbulent past.

### Historical Names Chronology: A Summary of Institutional Wanderlust

*   **May 1896-September 1900:** Imperial Chinese Railway College. The very beginning, before the world decided to intervene.
*   **September 1900-May 1905:** A period of unfortunate school closure, thanks to the invasion of the Qing empire by the Eight-Nation Alliance. Even universities aren't immune to inconvenient geopolitics.
*   **October 1905-March 1906:** Tangshan Railway College, Imperial Railways of North China. A phoenix from the ashes, albeit with a new address.
*   **April 1906-December 1907:** Tangshan Engineering & Mining College, Imperial Railways of North China. Expanding its repertoire, as institutions do.
*   **January 1908-December 1912:** Tangshan Engineering & Mining College (by the Ministry of Posts and Communications). A shift in ministerial oversight, but the name remained largely consistent.
*   **August 1913-July 1921:** Tangshan Engineering College. A simpler, more direct title.
*   **July 1921-September 1922:** Tangshan College, Chiao Tung University. Becoming part of a larger, nascent university system.
*   **September 1922-February 1928:** Tangshan University. Briefly shedding the "Chiao Tung" prefix.
*   **February 1928-June 1928:** Tangshan Chiao Tung University. Re-embracing the "Chiao Tung" identity.
*   **June 1928-August 1928:** The Second Chiao Tung University. A rather uninspired, if numerically accurate, designation.
*   **September 1928-August 1931:** Tangshan Civil Engineering College, Chiao Tung University. Specializing its focus within the broader university.
*   **September 1931-August 1937:** Tangshan Engineering College, Chiao Tung University. A slight modification, but largely stable for a few years.
*   **August 1937-January 1942:** Tangshan Engineering College, National Chiao Tung University. The wartime era begins, with a "National" prefix.
*   **January 1942-August 1946:** Guizhou Division, National Chiao Tung University. Forced into internal exile in Guizhou.
*   **August 1946-July 1949:** National Tangshan Engineering College. A return to Tangshan, and a more streamlined name, post-war.
*   **July 1949-August 1950:** Tangshan Engineering College, Jiaotong University of China. Under the new People's Republic.
*   **August 1950-May 1952:** Tangshan Engineering College, Northern Jiaotong University. Another slight adjustment in the broader Jiaotong university family.
*   **May 1952-March 1972:** Tangshan Institute of Railway. A more focused identity after departmental adjustments.
*   **March 1972-present:** [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University). The current, and hopefully final, name.

In 1928, after the establishment of the national government, Jiaotong University was indeed re-established by the Ministry of Communication, with its headquarter strategically placed in Shanghai. The Tangshan institution, during this period of reorganization, assumed the name of Tangshan Civil Engineering College of Jiaotong University.

