## Notable alumni

The legacy of [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University) is significantly defined by the accomplishments of its alumni, many of whom have made indelible marks in their respective fields, particularly within engineering and broader societal contributions.

*   [**Mao Yisheng**](/Mao_Yisheng): A towering figure in Chinese engineering, [Mao Yisheng](/Mao_Yisheng) is widely recognized as an unparalleled expert on bridge construction. His contributions to the field were not merely theoretical; he oversaw the design and construction of numerous critical bridges, shaping [China](/China)'s infrastructure. Beyond his engineering prowess, he was also a prominent social activist, demonstrating a rare blend of technical genius and civic engagement. He truly was a bridge builder, both literal and metaphorical.
*   [**Tung-Yen Lin**](/Tung-Yen_Lin): An eminent structural engineer whose work revolutionized modern construction. [Tung-Yen Lin](/Tung-Yen_Lin) is best known as the pioneering force behind standardizing the use of prestressed concrete. His innovations allowed for the creation of stronger, more efficient, and more aesthetically daring structures, profoundly influencing architectural and engineering practices worldwide. The man who made concrete less… flaccid. A true innovator, if one can truly innovate with concrete.
*   [**Jianyou Cao**](/Jianyou_Cao): A foundational figure in the electrification of [China](/China)'s railway system, [Jianyou Cao](/Jianyou_Cao) was one of the earliest and most significant contributors to this transformative endeavor. His expertise in electric power systems was such that he became a distinguished member of the Chinese Academy of Sciences. Furthermore, he holds the esteemed title of being the very founder of the school of electrical engineering at [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University), laying the academic groundwork for generations of electrical engineers. The architect of electrified railways and the very foundation of the university's electrical engineering department. A man who understood the power of a good current, both literally and academically.